{{More footnotes|date=April 2009}} {{Infobox animal | name = Enos | image = Mercury-Atlas 5 Enos with handler.jpg | image_upright = | caption = Enos with handler | birth_name = | othername = | species = Chimpanzee | breed = | gender = Male | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = November 4, 1962 | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | nationality = | occupation = | employer = NASA | role = First chimpanzee to achieve Earth orbit | years_active = 1960-62 | known = | tricks = | awards = | title = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | owner = | residence = | parents = | children = | weight = | height = | appearance = | namedafter = | website = }}
[[Image:Chimpanzee_Enos_before_the_flight_of_Mercury-Atlas_5.jpg|right|thumb|280px|Enos being prepared for insertion into the [[Mercury-Atlas 5]] capsule in 1961.]] '''Enos''' (d. November 4, 1962) was the second [[chimpanzee]] launched into space by [[NASA]]. He was the first [[chimpanzee]], and third [[hominid]] after [[cosmonaut]]s [[Yuri Gagarin]] and [[Gherman Titov]], to achieve Earth orbit. Enos' flight occurred on November 29, 1961.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
Enos was brought from the Miami Rare Bird Farm on April 3, 1960. He completed more than 1,250 training hours at the [[University of Kentucky]] and Holloman [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] Base. Training was more intense for him than for his predecessor [[Ham the Chimp|Ham]], because Enos was exposed to [[weightlessness]] and higher [[g-force|''g'']]s for longer periods of time. His training included psychomotor instruction and aircraft flights.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
Enos was selected for flight only three days before launch. Two months prior, [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration|NASA]] launched [[Mercury Atlas 4]] on September 13, 1961, to conduct an identical mission with a "crewman simulator" on board. Enos flew into space aboard [[Mercury Atlas 5]] on November 29, 1961. He completed his first orbit in 1 hour and 28.5 minutes.<ref>Animals In Space: From Research Rockets to the Space Shuttle, Chris Dubbs and [[Colin Burgess (author)|Colin Burgess]], 2007</ref>
Enos was scheduled to complete three orbits, but the mission was aborted after two due to two issues: capsule overheating and a malfunctioning "avoidance conditioning" test subjecting the primate to 76 electrical shocks. The capsule was brought aboard the [[USS Stormes|USS ''Stormes'']] (DD-780) in the late afternoon and Enos was immediately taken below deck by his Air Force handlers. The ''Stormes'' arrived in Bermuda the next day.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
Enos's flight was a full dress rehearsal for the next Mercury launch on February 20, 1962, which would make [[John Glenn]] the first American to orbit Earth, after astronauts [[Alan Shepard, Jr.]] and [[Gus Grissom]]'s successful suborbital space flights. On November 4, 1962, Enos died of [[shigellosis]]-related [[dysentery]], which was resistant to then-known antibiotics. He was constantly observed for two months before his death. Pathologists reported no symptoms that could be attributed or related to his previous space flight. Many believe Enos's remains were dissected like [[Ham the Chimp|Ham]], who was extensively studied postmortem at the Armed Forces Institute of Pathology. Some of Ham's remains, minus the skeleton (which remained with AIP), were buried at the [[International Space Hall of Fame]] in New Mexico. Recent attempts by space scholars to locate Enos's remains were unsuccessful. Post-mortem study was undertaken. His remains were then packed and sent to the Smithsonian Institute according to Dr. James E. Cook Veterinary Pathologist who was involved in Enos' autopsy and was also the Head of the Chimp Consortium at Holloman AFB at the time of Enos' death.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
