'''Otto Gold''' (18 May 1909 – 7 April 1977) was a [[Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovak]] [[figure skater]] and coach.
Gold, who competed in men's singles, won the silver medal at the [[1930 European Figure Skating Championships]] in Berlin.<ref name="Hines2011">{{cite book|author=James R. Hines|title=Historical Dictionary of Figure Skating|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSEkqy6BS44C&pg=PA301&dq=%22Otto+Gold%22|date=2011-04-22|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-7085-7|pages=301}}</ref><ref name="Hines2015">{{cite book|author=James R Hines|title=Figure Skating in the Formative Years: Singles, Pairs, and the Expanding Role of Women|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=ru&id=KD_oBgAAQBAJ&v=snippet&q=%22Otto+Gold%22|date=30 March 2015|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-09704-1|pages=}}</ref>
He began coaching in 1932. He coached [[Sonia Henie]] at the [[1935 World Figure Skating Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mary Rose Not Yet At Peak: Otto Gold, Her Instructor, Sees Improvement|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/39328491/?terms=Otto%2BGold|accessdate=24 July 2017|work=The Winnipeg Tribune|date=2 February 1942|page=15|language=en}}</ref>
In 1937, he moved to [[Ontario]], Canada, where he began a four-decade coaching career at the [[Minto Skating Club]]. He was one of the first coaches of 1948 Olympic champion [[Barbara Ann Scott]], and also worked in Vancouver, Connecticut and Lake Placid. He has been recognised for raising the level of figure skating in North America.<ref name="hof">{{cite web|title=1990 Canadian Figure Skating Hall of Fame Induction|url=https://skatecanada.ca/1990-canadian-figure-skating-hall-of-fame-induction/|publisher=Skate Canada|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref>
In April 1977, Gold died in a Toronto hospital from injuries caused by a fire at his apartment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Otto Gold dies in fire|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/49989677/?terms=Otto%2BGold|accessdate=24 July 2017|work=The Ottawa Journal|date=9 April 1977|page=40|language=en}}</ref>
His daughter, Frances Gold Lynn, was a figure skater who placed fourth at the [[1962 U.S. Figure Skating Championships]] and later became a coach.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baran|first1=Nancy|title=Interest in Figure Skating Sparked by Olympic Star|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/60252327/?terms=Otto%2BGold|accessdate=24 July 2017|work=The Bridgeport Post|date=8 May 1977|page=101|language=en}}</ref> He was inducted into the [[Skate Canada Hall of Fame|Canadian Figure Skating Hall of Fame]] in its inaugural class of 1990.<ref name="hof"/>
